      deepDive:
        "Mechanical intelligence isn't a single skill — it's a cognitive orientation. Your internal logic engine builds models of how things work by processing direct sensory input rather than abstract descriptions. Where a theoretical thinker reads about how an engine works and builds a conceptual model, you listen to it run, feel the vibrations, watch the timing, and build a model grounded in physical reality. The result is understanding that's both deeper and harder to articulate: you know things in a way that doesn't translate cleanly into language because the knowledge was never linguistic to begin with. This extends far beyond literal mechanics. You apply the same approach to software systems (poking at the code to see what happens, not reading the documentation), organizational problems (observing the actual workflow rather than the org chart), and even people (watching what they do, not what they say). Your models are built from observation, not theory, which makes them resistant to the kind of elegant-but-wrong reasoning that trips up more abstract thinkers. The development opportunity: learning to translate your mechanical understanding into language that others can use. Your models are often more accurate than anyone else's in the room — but if you can't communicate them, their value is limited to what you personally can execute.",
