      deepDive:
        "Your efficiency comes from how your internal logic engine evaluates solutions. It doesn't optimize for comprehensiveness or theoretical completeness — it optimizes for what actually fixes the problem with minimum resource expenditure. This means you'll often find solutions that more methodical types miss, because you're not constrained by the 'proper' approach. You'll use the tool that works rather than the tool that's designated. You'll skip three steps in the procedure if those steps don't contribute to the outcome. You'll rig a temporary fix that holds for years because it addresses the actual failure point rather than the documented one. This efficiency extends to communication. You say what needs saying and stop. In meetings, you're the person who's been quiet for forty-five minutes and then makes the one observation that reframes the entire discussion — because your internal logic engine was processing while everyone else was performing. The growth edge: your efficiency can look like disengagement. When you skip the process and jump to the solution, people who value procedure feel bypassed. When you communicate in minimum viable sentences, people who value elaboration feel dismissed. Learning when to show your work — not because the work requires it, but because the audience does — is a social skill that amplifies your technical competence.",
